content:
We need to analyze case: young male, intermittent dysuria, hematuria, proteinuria, RBC casts, low complement C3/C4, positive ANA, possible glomerulonephritis. Could be lupus nephritis (SLE), but low C4 also, ANA positive. Could be post-infectious GN? Usually low C3, normal C4. Here both low. Could be membranoproliferative GN (MPGN) secondary to complement consumption (C3 nephritic factor). Could be IgA nephropathy (but complement usually normal). Could be ANCA-associated vasculitis (e.g., GPA, MPA) - but ANCA pending. Could be infection-related GN with strep? No recent infection. Could be drug-induced interstitial nephritis? but RBC casts and dysmorphic RBCs suggest glomerular. Also proteinuria 3+, edema, hypertension. So likely rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis (RPGN) secondary to lupus (class III/IV) or ANCA vasculitis or MPGN.

Given low complement and ANA positive, lupus nephritis high suspicion. Age 24 male is less common but possible. Need anti-dsDNA, anti-Sm. Also need complement low.

Thus primary diagnosis: Lupus nephritis (class III/IV) presenting as RPGN.

Confidence maybe 0.7.

Differentials: ANCA-associated vasculitis (GPA/MPA), Post-infectious GN, Membranoproliferative GN (type I), IgA nephropathy, Alport syndrome (but not typical). Provide 4-5.

Key findings: dysuria (maybe infection?), but RBC casts, proteinuria, low complement, ANA+, hypertension, edema, renal enlargement.

Tests: Anti-dsDNA, anti-Sm, ENA panel, ANCA (c-ANCA, p-ANCA), complement repeat, renal biopsy (urgent), urine protein quantification (24h), serology for hepatitis B/C (MPGN), anti-GBM antibodies, complement levels, repeat labs.

Management: immediate hospitalization, start IV methylprednisolone, consider cyclophosphamide, possibly mycophenolate mofetil, antihypertensives (ACE inhibitor), diuretics, avoid nephrotoxic drugs. Consult nephrology (urgent), rheumatology.

Red flags: rapidly rising creatinine, hypertension, edema, RBC casts, low complement, possible RPGN.

Now create JSON.

We need ICD-10 codes: Lupus nephritis = N00.9? Actually lupus nephritis is under systemic lupus erythematosus with renal involvement: M32.14 (SLE with renal involvement, class III/IV). Use M32.14.

ANCA-associated vasculitis: M31.7 (Microscopic polyangiitis) or M31.3 (Granulomatosis with polyangiitis). We'll pick M31.3.

Post-infectious GN: N00.1 (Acute postinfectious glomerulonephritis). MPGN: N02.8 (Other membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis). IgA nephropathy: N02.3.

